'''''Best Of...''''', also referred to a '''''Sia: Best Of...''''',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|title=Say hi to Sia's first greatest hits set|accessdate=23 May 2012|first=Antonino|last=Tati|work=Cream|date=12 March 2012|location=Elizabeth Bay, New South Wales, Australia}}</ref> is the first [[greatest hits album]] (seventh album overall) by Australian singer-songwriter [[Sia Furler|Sia]], released in Australia on 30 March 2012 through the Sydney-based [[independent record label]] [[Inertia (independent record company)|Inertia]].<ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/best-of-r2456414|title=Best Of...|accessdate=21 May 2012|work=''[[Allmusic]]''|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]}}</ref> The [[Compilation album|compilation]] includes tracks from four of Sia's previous studio albums: ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'' (2002), ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004), ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2008) and ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010). Also included are two tracks featuring Sia as a guest vocalist ("[[Destiny (Zero 7 song)|Destiny]]" by [[Zero 7]] and "[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]" by [[David Guetta]]), "My Love" from [[The Twilight Saga: Eclipse (soundtrack)|''The Twilight Saga: Eclipse'' film soundtrack]], plus a remixed version of "Buttons" by Brazilian rock band [[CSS (band)|CSS]]. The album was announced in February 2012, shortly after Sia claimed she would be retiring. Some online music stores offered Sia's music DVD ''[[TV Is My Parent]]'' as a bonus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jbhifionline.com.au/music/pop-rock/best-of/663247 |title=Best Of... (Bonus DVD) <U+2013> Sia|publisher=[[JB Hi-Fi]]|accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref> Overall, critical reception of the album was positive, though many reviewers criticized select tracks. ''Best Of...'' debuted at number 30 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] the week of April 15 and reached a peak position of number 27 the following week.

==Background and promotion==
The album was announced in February 2012, shortly after Sia made a statement claiming she was retiring.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/sia-announces-best-of-album-after-qutting-last-week/|title=Sia Announces 'Best Of' Album After Quiting Last Week|work=[[Music Feeds]]|date=24 February 2012|accessdate=22 May 22 2012|first=John|last=Ritchie|location=Sydney, Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-news/artists/2012/02/24/sia-releasing-greatest-hits-album/|title=Sia releasing greatest hits album|date=24 February 2012|accessdate=22 May 2012|work=The Music Network|publisher=Peer Group Media|first=Olivia|last=Kim}}</ref><ref name=Moran>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/insider/jonathon-moran-explores-the-real-sia-kate-isobelle-furler/story-e6frewt9-1226281363986|title=Jonathon Moran explores the real Sia Kate Isobelle Furler|date=26 February 2012|accessdate=29 May 2012|first=Jonathon|last=Moran|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|The Daily Telegraph]]|location=Sydney, Australia|publisher=[[News Limited]]}}</ref> ''Best Of...'' received promotion in various forms. IE Music/Inertia released a promotional video on [[YouTube]] in March 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gX_ynuAMn9I|title=Sia 'Best Of' (Out on IE Music/Inertia)|accessdate=1 June 2012|date=18 March 2012|publisher=IE Music/[[Inertia (independent record company)|Inertia]]}}</ref> One day prior to the album's release, ''[[Oyster (magazine)|Oyster]]'' magazine commemorated Sia's career by publishing their list of her top five collaborations.<ref name=Oyster>{{cite journal|url=http://oystermag.com/top-5-sia-collaborations|title=Top 5: Sia Collaborations |date=29 March 2012|accessdate=23 May 2012|work=[[Oyster (magazine)|Oyster]]|issn=1322-6495|location=Surry Hills, New South Wales, Australia}}</ref>  The compilation album and a Sia tote bag, among other prizes, were included in a competition held by ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/win/2012/5/win-a-mojo-%E2%80%98dutchie%E2%80%99-bike-thanks-to-sia/|title=Win a Mojo 'Dutchie' Bike thanks to Sia|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|accessdate=23 May 2012|date=May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inertia-music.com/2012/05/win-in-celebration-of-sia%E2%80%99s-new-%E2%80%9Cbest-of%E2%80%9D-album-cosmo-has-a-huge-competition/|title=Win: In celebration of Sia's new "Best Of" album, Cosmo has a huge competition!|accessdate=23 May 2012|publisher=Inertia|date=17 May 2012}}</ref> In April 2012, ''Music Australia Guide'' (''Mag'') offered copies of the album to readers as part of a "[[Product sample|freebie]]" giveaway.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.musicaustraliaguide.com/features/2012/04/giveaways|title=Giveaways!|date=April 12, 2012|accessdate=23 May 2012|work=Music Australia Guide|publisher=Slattery Media Group|first=Antonia|last=Magee}}</ref>

==Content==
''Best Of...'' contains eighteen tracks spanning fifteen years of music from Sia's career, including collaborative work with [[Zero 7]] and other artists.<ref name=Luna>{{cite journal|url=http://lunadigital.tv/sia-releases-best-of-album/|title=Sia Releases 'Best Of' Album|accessdate=15 June 2012|work=Luna|location=Adelaide, Australia|publisher=Arcadia Co. Pty. Ltd.|first=Laura|last=Conroy|date=30 March 2012}}</ref> Fourteen tracks come from four of Sia's previous studio albums. "Taken for Granted", representing the oldest material on the compilation, is the only song from Sia's 2002 album ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]''.<ref name=Healing>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-r594275/review|title=Healing Is Difficult|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=21 May 2012|first=Jon|last=O'Brien}}</ref><ref name=Rave>{{cite journal|url=http://www.ravemagazine.com.au/content/view/32335/|title=Sia <U+2013> Best Of|accessdate=1 June 2012|date=9 April 2012|work=Rave Magazine|location=Brisbane, Australia|first=Alasdair|last=Duncan}}</ref> "Numb", "Where I Belong", "[[Breathe Me]]" and "Sweet Potato" all appeared on Sia's 2004 album ''[[Colour the Small One]]''.<ref name=Colour>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-r679531|title=Colour the Small One|first=Jon|last=O'Brien|accessdate=21 May 21 2012|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref> Tracks from her 2008 album ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' include "The Girl You Lost to Cocaine",<ref name=Davies>{{cite web|url=http://www.artshub.com.au/au/news-article/reviews/performing-arts/sia-best-of-188682|title=Sia <U+2013> Best Of...|first=Freya|last=Davies|accessdate=21 May 2012|work=ArtsHub|publisher=ArtsHub Holdings|date=10 April 2012}}</ref> "Day Too Soon", [[Ray Davies]]' "[[I Go to Sleep]]", "[[Soon We'll Be Found]]" and "Buttons".<ref name=Some>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-r1290410/review|title=Some People Have Real Problems|accessdate=21 May 2012|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation|first=Stewart|last=Mason}}</ref> "[[Clap Your Hands (Sia song)|Clap Your Hands]]", "Bring Night", "[[You've Changed (song)|You've Changed]]" and "The Fight" originally appeared on Sia's previous studio album ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010).<ref name=Davies/><ref name=Born>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-r1822615/review|title=We Are Born|first=K. Ross|last=Hoffman|accessdate=21 May 2012|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref>

The remaining four tracks represent collaborative works, one soundtrack appearance and a remix. "[[Destiny (Zero 7 song)|Destiny]]" first appeared on the British duo [[Zero 7]]'s album ''[[Simple Things (Zero 7 album)|Simple Things]]'' (2001); the track features vocal performances by Sia and [[Sophie Barker]].<ref name=Davies/><ref name=Simple>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-r538438/review|title=Simple Things|accessdate=22 May 2012|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation|first=Tim|last=DiGravina}}</ref> "My Love" appeared on [[The Twilight Saga: Eclipse (soundtrack)|''The Twilight Saga: Eclipse'' film soundtrack]] (2010).<ref name=Eclipse>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/the-twilight-saga-eclipse-r1806137/review|title=The Twilight Saga: Eclipse|accessdate=23 May 2012|first=Heather|last=Phares|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref><ref name=StarOnline>{{cite news|url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/play/2012/03/21/the-best-of-sia/74497|title=The Best Of<U+2026> Sia|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=29 May 2012|work=[[Sydney Star Observer]]|issn=0819-5129|oclc=	26727666}}</ref> "[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]", written by Sia, [[David Guetta]], Giorgio Tuinfort and [[Afrojack|Nick van de Wall]], first appeared on Guetta's 2011 album ''[[Nothing but the Beat]]''.<ref name=Nothing>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/nothing-but-the-beat-r2262362/review|title=Nothing But the Beat|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=22 May 2012|first=David|last=Jeffries}}</ref>

